1 Data and Code

The R code for the analysis of the combined Phase 1 and Phase 2 data are in a GitHub repository. This repository is private for now; send me a request to access it with your GitHub user ID at lizhare@gmail.com. The goal is open the code for peer review and the community.

Two spreadsheets received from James are imported:

  • Phase 1: Detection-dog-survey.xlsx
  • Phase 2: DD Survey 20220714-20221104.xlsx

2 Demographic Description

The data analyzed here include 1117 dogs with dogs collected in Phase 1 (686 dogs) and Phase 2 (431 dogs). In phase 1, there was a problem collecting data about whether dogs were neutered. Also in phase 1, three questions about chasing were excluded. Because they are missing fro most dogs in this data set, they are excluded from the whole analysis (previous analysis of Phase 2 shows the three chasing items separate into a factor).

After merging the data from Phase 1 and Phase 2, we found that 58 dogs had repeated records. 56 were removed by selecting the record with the latest date, because they will have better data on neutering. Two repeated records were completed on the same day, so the ones with fewer missing CBARQ items were retained.

2.2 Breed and Breed Group

The questionnaire provided a multiple-choice question asking about the dog’s breed. We assigned breeds to AKC breed groups to potentially avoid having a large number of categories with small numbers of dogs. If a breed was not listed with AKC, breeds, groups were chosen according to the breed’s purpose and history.

Overall, there were 886 purebred dogs. There were 92 dogs listed as “cross-breed” (were there instructions to use this specifically for known crosses like labradoodles?) and 70 dogslisted as “mixed-breed.”

According to Watkins (2021), items should be removed if they have skewness > 2.0 or kurtosis > 7.0. These items would violate the assumptions of the Pearson correlation coefficients that factor analysis is based on. (Do we need to consider the items as ordinal discrete values?)

There are 17 items with skewness > 2.0 including AGG09, AGG11, AGG12, AGG13, AGG15, AGG17, AGG19, FEAR21, FEAR23, FEAR24, FEAR25, FEAR30, SEPR34, MISC55, MISC58, MISC68, MISC69.

4 Conclusions for Factor Analysis

Data will ba analyzed with the items as ordered factors rather than numeric variables for the following reasons:

  • Many items have a large number of values of 0
  • The p-value for the Shapiro test is always near 0, indicating that the data do not come from a normal distribution.
  • Some items have high skewness and kurtosis. The kurtosis is particularly high for some of the items.
